I asked ChatGPT about the flaws in America's political incentive structure, and here's what it shared:

Now, how would YOU tweak these incentives for a better political landscape? üëáüèøüó≥Ô∏èüí¨ #USPolitics #Incentives #ChangeTheGame

The incentive structure in American politics, like in any political system, is complex and can have both positive and negative consequences. Here are some of the downfalls or challenges associated with the current incentive structure in American politics:

1. Partisanship and Polarization: One significant issue is the incentive for politicians to prioritize party loyalty over bipartisan cooperation. In a highly polarized environment, politicians may fear primary challenges from within their own party if they are seen as compromising with the opposing party, leading to gridlock and dysfunction in government.

1. Short-Term Focus: Elected officials often face incentives to prioritize short-term gains and reelection over long-term policy solutions. This can lead to a focus on quick wins and policies that appeal to their base rather than addressing complex, long-term challenges.

3. Fundraising Pressure: Political campaigns require significant funding, and candidates often spend a considerable amount of time fundraising. This can lead to concerns about undue influence from wealthy donors or special interest groups and may detract from time spent on policymaking.

4. Negative Campaigning: The current incentive structure sometimes rewards negative campaigning and attack ads. Candidates may find that attacking opponents is an effective way to gain media attention and energize their base.

5. Incumbency Advantage: Incumbent politicians often have a built-in advantage, making it challenging for new or third-party candidates to compete. This can lead to a lack of competitive elections and reduced accountability.

6. Media and Sensationalism: Media outlets may have incentives to prioritize sensational or controversial stories over substantive policy discussions. This can contribute to the focus on personality-driven politics rather than policy issues.

7. Gerrymandering: Incentives for state legislators to draw district boundaries in ways that favor their own party can result in uncompetitive districts and reduce political accountability.

8. Lobbying and Special Interests: The influence of lobbying groups and special interests can be significant, as they have the resources and incentives to shape policy decisions in their favor, potentially at the expense of the broader public interest.

9. Primary Systems: Primary elections can lead to the selection of candidates who appeal to the more extreme elements of their party's base, potentially making it difficult for more moderate candidates to succeed in general elections.

10. Lack of Civic Engagement: The current incentive structure may not always encourage high levels of civic engagement and voter turnout, as some voters may feel disillusioned or believe that their voices do not matter.

These are some of the challenges associated with the current incentive structure in American politics. 
Addressing these issues often requires comprehensive political and electoral reforms, as well as changes in political culture and public expectations.

Last year I emailed the Canadian Anti-Hate Network to ask how they defined the "far-right," and if they were at all concerned with the potential for left-wing extremism in Canada. Here's the full response I received from CAHN's Executive Director Evan Balgord:

The far-right movement sees itself as the true people fighting against a corrupt ruling class.

(Nothing wrong with that first part. Populism isn't necessarily a bad thing.)

It is tolerant of racism, antisemitism, misogyny and anti-LGBTQ+ sentiments in its midst, either because they are embraced, seen as less important than maintaining movement cohesion, or because the allegations are seen themselves as an invention of corrupt media. They see their opposition as unCanadian and undeserving of rights, and that often extends to equity-deserving groups. They want to take power (in an election or not) and use that power to persecute their enemies. They are against democratic norms like the institution of journalism and the peaceful transition of power. Many of them discuss putting their enemies on trial for treason and hardline elements say they want to ‚Äúgenocide‚Äù them.

So the far-right isn't regular small-c conservatism, unless you think regular conservatism is tolerant of racism and wants to do away with democracy. I think it's the responsibility of regular conservatives to make sure those lines don't blur and to protect their position from extremists.

The far-right movement is a threat to democracy and elements within it inspire the vast majority of modern-day Ideologically Motivated Violent Extremism (IMVE), including mass murders.

(What's attributed or blamed on the 'far-left' doesn't even come close. Go take a look at CSIS statements, or the FBIs).

The ideologies of the far-right movement and the racist, anti-women, and anti-LGBTQ+ beliefs inside it are often based on simplistic, conspiratorial interpretations of the world that replicate by the spread of disinformation and misinformation.

We have always been very clear that not every convoy supporter or antivaxxer is a racist or a white supremacist. I have empathy for people who have lost their jobs or relationships because they started to believe in conspiracies. People have real and valid grievances that our politics are failing to address, especially those stemming from income inequality. The empty promises of the far-right are, understandably, appealing - and can attract otherwise intelligent people. We need a real political alternative that would make everyone's lives significantly better.

An important commentary by a British reporter living and working in Russia on the state of Western journalism in covering the Ukraine War. #cdnpolitics #USPolitics

Predictions tend to make fools of us all, so I don‚Äôt make many. But back in march I tweeted this. Many in the alternative press and military analysts on X knew it too. The failed Ukrainian counter offensive has not just been a disaster for Ukraine. It has been a monumental failure of NATO intelligence and has laid bare the intellectual ineptitude of the Western mainstream press. How could this have happened?

I did expect Ukraine to have more success than they did. And many Russians did too. When I drove through Zaphorozhie region recently I saw newly dug defensive lines as far south as the Black Sea. They were prepared.

I‚Äôve spent must of the last year in Donbass. It‚Äôs tough on the frontlines. Much tougher than Russia would like to admit. War is hell. 

But the reality is that insufficient air or artillery superiority, Ukrainian generals warning they weren‚Äôt ready. A year long self deluding media campaign about the incompetency of the Russian army. It was clear to those in the know it would be a disaster. If ukriane did have success, Russia has such great reserves they would have reversed it. 

Absurd, deluded articles about Russian conscripts who would apparently flee British Challenger 2‚Äôs. Think tanks obsessed with the propaganda war while Russia lays millions of mines.

Anyone who even suggests peace is labeled a Kremlin asset. Meaning anyone in politics, journalism or civil society who questions the inept and self destructive policies risks losing their job and their ability to support their families. This isn‚Äôt freedom. It‚Äôs a fear culture. A form of intellectual lobotomy that is destroying Britains ability to form prosperous policy. 

The shocking standard of British reporting is damaging British interests by being so inept in their judgements. By attempting to fool the public they are also fooling themselves and members of parliament. Most of whom know little of international affairs bar what they read in these same papers. 

As a reporter in Donbass I was often asked to comment on events elsewhere in Ukraine. I would look at the mainstream press to do so as they have many reporters in Ukraine. Over the course of the war I have simply found them too unreliable to treat as credible sources. When a Ukrainian missile hit an apartment block around the corner from me in Donetsk. Europe is suffering a crisis of leadership. Corporations and big money have become too powerful. And we have shipped out our foreign policy to the US. Naively believing their interests are the same as ours. They are not. 

There are few real European patriots left in positions of power or in the media. And even fewer with the courage and intellectual ability to read the changing tides of history and of the new path that Europe must inevitably plough.

A British writer penned the best description of Donald Trump I‚Äôve ever read:

‚ÄúWhy do some British people not like Donald Trump?‚Äù 

A few things spring to mind. Trump lacks certain qualities which the British traditionally esteem. For instance, he has no class, no charm, no coolness, no credibility, no compassion, no wit, no warmth, no wisdom, no subtlety, no sensitivity, no self-awareness, no humility, no honour and no grace ‚Äì all qualities, funnily enough, with which his predecessor Mr. Obama was generously blessed. So for us, the stark contrast does rather throw Trump‚Äôs limitations into embarrassingly sharp relief. 

Plus, we like a laugh. And while Trump may be laughable, he has never once said anything wry, witty or even faintly amusing ‚Äì not once, ever. I don‚Äôt say that rhetorically, I mean it quite literally: not once, not ever. And that fact is particularly disturbing to the British sensibility ‚Äì for us, to lack humour is almost inhuman. But with Trump, it‚Äôs a fact. He doesn‚Äôt even seem to understand what a joke is ‚Äì his idea of a joke is a crass comment, an illiterate insult, a casual act of cruelty. 

Trump is a troll. And like all trolls, he is never funny and he never laughs; he only crows or jeers. And scarily, he doesn‚Äôt just talk in crude, witless insults ‚Äì he actually thinks in them. His mind is a simple bot-like algorithm of petty prejudices and knee-jerk nastiness. 

There is never any under-layer of irony, complexity, nuance or depth. It‚Äôs all surface. Some Americans might see this as refreshingly upfront. Well, we don‚Äôt. We see it as having no inner world, no soul. And in Britain we traditionally side with David, not Goliath. All our heroes are plucky underdogs: Robin Hood, Dick Whittington, Oliver Twist. Trump is neither plucky, nor an underdog. He is the exact opposite of that. He‚Äôs not even a spoiled rich-boy, or a greedy fat-cat. He‚Äôs more a fat white slug. A Jabba the Hutt of privilege.
